  <div>
    <h2>Initial Attempt</h2>
    <p>
      Our initial idea was to use two commonly used feature/shape detection algorithms to differentiate between forks, knives, and spoons.
    </p>
    <p>
      To differentiate forks from the other two utensil types, we decided to use the Harris Corner detector algorithm. This transform assigns every pixel in an image a score which relates to its “corner-ness”, where a corner is defined as a point with a high image gradient in most directions. If any given utensil was detected to have multiple corners after applying this transform, the system would classify the utensil as a fork.
    </p>
    <p>
      To differentiate spoons from knives, we planned to use the Hough Transform - a tranform commonly used to detect circles and ellipses in images - to detect the elliptical head of the spoon. The Hough Transform iterates through image pixels and possible radial lengths and assigns a liklihood score to each pixel. The presence of a pixel in the transform with a very high value indicates the existence of an ellipse centered at that pixel. Hence, if such a pixel existed after applying the transform on a utensil image, the system would classify the utensil as a spoon.
    </p>
    <p>
      If the supplied utensil was found to be neither a fork nor a spoon, the system would classify the utensil as a knife.
    </p>
